      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Knowing when not to attempt a tire change yourself helps prevent injury and further vehicle damage. Professional roadside assistance is safer in hazardous or complex situations.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from epa.gov; osha.gov; ecfr.gov; csa.fmcsa.dot.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Unsafe roadside conditions or heavy traffic</li><li>Lack of proper tools or vehicle-specific knowledge</li><li>Damaged or missing spare tire</li><li>Vehicle instability or jack failure</li><li>Physical inability or health concerns</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>If your vehicle is on a busy highway shoulder with poor visibility, calling roadside assistance is safer than changing the tire yourself.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify scenarios where you would choose professional help over self-service.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Attempting a tire change in unsafe conditions can lead to accidents or injury.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> epa.gov; osha.gov; ecfr.gov; csa.fmcsa.dot.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
